metadata.name: Lucky Oracles #19
metadata.description:
"Lucky Oracles" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

Eko33, is a Swiss-French generative artist who has been at the forefront of digital arts since 1999 when he started writing code to create generative artworks and installations. He made his debut using a Commodore SX-64 and floppy disks. Since then, his work has been exhibited in Museums, International art fairs, and biennales. His work is focused on nonfigurative, generative art while using custom algorithms and innovative technology.

Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/ Official Twitter account: https://twitter.com/eko3316 Official Instagram account: https://www.instagram.com/eko33studio/ https://linktr.ee/eko33 "I create deterministic generative art based on crypto hash seeds. Maximizing algorithmic diversity."

If you want to receive an e-mail alert when I release new artwork subscribe here => https://eko33.com/email-alerts

metadata.name: Modern Times #160
metadata.description:
Created by Eko33, a generative artist featured at the Tezos Ecosystem Exhibition (Art Basel Miami 2021).

This generative artwork creates a limited series of distinctive artworks based on unique hash seeds.

The algorithmic approach of this collection generates a broad spectrum of unique outcomes, inspired by the "giant machine" from the movie "Modern Times."

Beyond a classic mechanical representation, Eko33 aims to convey multiple emotions while embracing the cold nature of algorithms.

Computer-generated generative art can be seen as a gigantic assembly line. Still, its true nature gives the artist complete freedom from all commercially available tools/constraints.

The collection "Modern Times" highlights the dark ages of generative arts using a bichromatic color palette and evolves toward the contemporary "Digital Renaissance" era using warmer, more acid and "pop" colors.

About Eko33:
Official fx(hash) page: https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/Eko33
Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/

metadata.name: Simple_Syrup_1 #30
metadata.description:
Simple_Syrup_1, by Stephen Boyd
May, 2022
Little India, Toronto, Canada.


_Project Description
"The staple cocktail sweetener more than earns its name, consisting, simply, of equal-parts granulated sugar and water. From there, the variations are endless."
https://www.liquor.com/recipes/simple-syrup/


"The variations are endless..." I think of simple syrup as an analogy for what I've seen during my brief time so far on fxhash. The combination of a platform and people bringing out endless variations of creativity. Each Project with the possibility for endless variation in the exploration of a limited number of features.

This is my first project released on fxhash. I'm grateful to everyone who founded fxhash and to everyone who has positively contributed to the community.

These images are comprised of clusters of coloured ellipses on a coloured background. Each cluster varies in their strokeWeight, position, transparency and colour values.

There are two primary variables that all other features are dependent on: the first being the number of clusters, and the second is the number of ellipses in each cluster (up to a maximum of 123 per cluster). From these two variables the rest of the visual attributes (eg. alpha vs strokeWeight, colour palettes, etc...) are determined.

A constant in all my work, including this project, is the use of PHI and a Fibonnaci sequence starting with 4 and 7 to determine layouts and relationships between elements in the image. If you look through the code you will find many instances of the numbers: 4, 7, 11, 18, 29, 47,....

There are 18 colour palettes for this project. They are adapted from Mark Rothko paintings as interpreted by Merritt Smith, (https://mmerrittsmith.github.io/about/). I refactored the original R files to work with Javascript here. You can find Merritt's original project on GitHub: https://github.com/mmerrittsmith/rothko .


_Interaction
You can export this image to PNG format at several different sizes.

I've added code that will re-render the iteration at each of the sizes listed below while retaining its exact characteristics. This is considerably better than trying to up or downscale an image.

Press t: thumbnail @ 200x200 
Press s: your current screen size 
Press p: print size @ 4800x4800 which is 16"@300dpi 
Press h: HD4K on the vertical @ 2160x2160 
Press m: Max size @ 10800x10800 This is a biiiig size


_Technology Used for Development
Made with Processing / P5.js
p5.js v1.4.1 February 02, 2022

metadata.name: Assemble #104
metadata.description:
Assemble is a 2D shape composition with a procedural background texture.

There are two types of shapes, squares and blobs, composed in a grid.

12 color palettes, procedurally generated using a GAN algorithm.

Available in [1:1] and [3:4] resolutions.

--------------------------------------------------

Keys [1-4]

1 - Variation (maintaining resolution)
2 - Variation (changing resolution)
3 - Change color (only in [3:4] resolution)
4 - Save canvas (Live View)

--------------------------------------------------

Made with p5.

-dePaula

metadata.name: Arcade Lights #30
metadata.description:
Click anywhere in the image to alter it as you see fit. Play around with it. Have fun!

Arcade Lights is inspired by a bunch of things that bring me joy: Playing video games in my youth, abstract and colorful street graffiti, playful long exposure light photography, wild nights out clubbing, funky retrofuturistic synthwave music.

Press 'p' or 'j' in live mode to save a png or jpg.

In live mode, open the brower's developer tools/devtools/web inspector and go to the console to learn how to produce a static live mode link for the exact image that you've clicked into existence.

Features:
17 vibrant palettes
5 playful ornament styles
3 distinct layouts
2 flow directions
3 draw orders
2 bend directions

I hope Arcade Lights will bring you as much joy as it has me <3

metadata.name: Bellissimas #120
metadata.description:
Expressive portraits inspired by @michelepetrelli 

The used techniques search in the unexplored field of mixing pfp layer based work and real-time generative algorithms changing and adding to the premade assets.

The pre-generated assets include original artworks by Petrelli, Imitations of Petrelli's work by @brutalisti, GAN generated artworks inspired by Petrelli using several different AI technologies.

Every generatively chosen layer combination is live-processed and generatively altered in aspects of color and shape. Then the generative algorithm proceed with captured color palettes and generate background and additional drawing over and under the initial layers. The final result as acquired by visualizing everything with live generative algorithm that give additional layer of uniqueness.

Project by  @michelepetrelli & @brutalisti, curated by XCOLLABS
